Higgs Boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate outburst in the summer.
There is an opinion that this boson participates in a mechanism that is responsible for all the matter in the universe.
Furthermore, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "less wrong" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - which has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no 100% certainty among physicists that Higgs's boson is involved.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle available that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week during the great physical congress in Kyoto is more likely to confirm it, but all the data is still missing so that we can have absolute certainty.
However, let's assume it's Higgs's boson, because the risk of mistake seems small, and let's see what it's really about.
In this world, there is an absolutely indisputable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be bypassed - and don't try too hard on it, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that the same law applies to it: Pauli's exclusionary principle, according to which two particles cannot take up the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" is roughly pronounced
It further divides the physical particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently obey Paul’s principle.
And at the other end, the bosons move, according to anarchists, who do not value anything at all - certainly not this principle, which means that they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way, quite amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley labs: the mesons that we leave here without notice, and the "force particles" that spread great natural forces and with which the Higgs bosons are the most common.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it is thanks to a boson with unusual banality: a photon, or "particles of light", which is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
That is, when the particles with an electric charge accelerate or change their direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, much like a shell thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) arises, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "carriers of force".
Stable field
It is the same with the Higgs boson, but with the difference that it is necessary to "disrupt" another field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to its excitation it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, as with the frozen level of the pond, which already consumes only a very large amount of balvan.
For this reason, it is necessary to use both a huge part accelerator and an accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large Hadron accelerator with injection joints is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
Analogies with the electromagnetic field are again useful for clarifying the relationship between Higgs and matter.
With an electromagnetic field, neither all particles nor all materials react.
Some, for example, magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep on the fridge on its own.
And the same is true that with the Higgs field not all particles react: those that do have a certain mass, while others (like photons, let’s look at it) don’t have it.
And Mrs. Nov<0xC3><0xA1>kov<0xC3><0xA1> is wondering, what are all these researches for, what "will they bring us"?
In terms of science, it is a confirmation of the validity of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to substantiate the examination of any discrepancy between SM observation and predictions.
Moreover, not many physicists literally wish to be able to find them, because the slightest difference could open the space of "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It is necessary to note that the model still has huge flaws, does not bring any clarification of gravity (ooh!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe's mass (again ooh!).
However, the CERN device has so far not revealed such discrepancies.
Responses
Responses to these researches in the everyday life of Mr. and Mrs. Novak can only be very difficult to predict, but the mistake would be to think that there would be none.
Look: at the very beginning of the 1960s, the laser pioneers in Bell’s laboratories had no idea of the revolution that caused their work.
