In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are ordinary account book depositors, controllers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users takes place, in fact, between two e-mail addresses by e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
This way, the network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of ordinary accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write down this new transaction in this book.
It takes place by solving the mathematical task assigned to computers, whose solver, a temporary central banker, will be entitled to write this additional line.
This is the process of cutting a file; i.e. transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital print.
Computers will "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then the whole "cuts".
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific print (worth zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check its correctness.
The transaction is then irretrievably displayed connected to the chain of all other transactions; any adjustment would result in a change of print.
If the user wants to pay twice the same money very quickly for the purpose of fraud (up to ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, because each of them has a different print.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is divided regularly into two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but it can be divided up to one hundred million, so there is room for margin here.
The difficulty of the task is also increased with the increasing level of calculation.
