"Actually, it has a long history of boredom," he said.
On the walls of Pompeii was found a Latin inscription concerning boredom, dating from the first century of our year.
And then there’s the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After looking at the research literature and presenting the idea to the target group about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience "I wanted to do something that would please me, but I was not able to."
The boredom differs from apathy by the fact that the person is not involved in anything, but wants to be.
He says there's no need to do anything about apathy.
He says that the core of boredom is “the disruption of the attention process associated with a bad mood and the feeling of slowly passing time.”
Fatigue can be a lot like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a mutual relationship, bored people tend to see a problem as an environment or a world, while people who are depressed see a problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored when we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to the tape on which the person read the article from the journal.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television show in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group didn’t hear it at all.
Those who heard the TV show quietly reported greater boredom than the other two groups — they had difficulty concentrating, but they weren’t sure why and attributed these difficulties to boredom.
When you’re trying to focus on a difficult or engaging task, distraction can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, “like finding the wrong parts on the factory line, dispersing music can help keep you from getting bored.”
In fact, he said, we now know that spinning and scratching, which is often seen as a sign of boredom, can actually help with boredom fight and keep people physically more alert.
