To help with the measurement of boredom in the 80s of the last century, scientists have developed a "Stairway to Addiction to boredom" (Boredom Proneness Scale).
The steps include questions like, "A lot of things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all."
Using these degrees, scientists found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimuli.
Teenagers are generally insecure.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
